# README Update Policy

After implementing any new feature, always update `README.md` before finishing.

## What counts as a new feature

- A new dashboard page or section in `app/streamlit_app.py`
- A new scoring function or batch utility in `core/scoring.py`
- A new model, artifact, or training step in `train.py`
- A new API endpoint or router in `api/routers/`
- A new config constant that changes behaviour (not just a rename)
- A new module added to `core/`

## What to update

| README section | Update when… |
|---|---|
| **Project Structure** | A new file or directory is added |
| **Dashboard Pages** table | A new Streamlit page is added or renamed |
| **Model Cutoff Dates** table | A new model is trained or a cutoff changes |
| **Quickstart** | The run/train steps change |

## Rules

- Edit the existing section — do not add a new top-level section unless the feature genuinely has no home.
- Keep descriptions to one sentence.
- Never update the README for refactors, bug fixes, or comment changes — only net-new user-visible functionality.
- Update `README.md` in the **same task/turn** as the feature, not as a follow-up.